WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.160
Thank you. This is Reese's Pieces. We named her that because her orange and brown spots

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:19.680
reminded us of the candy. And I work from home, so Reese and I get to hang out a lot.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.320
And whenever I get stuck on a particularly thorny R problem, I talk to her. She's kind

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:28.879
of my sounding board, and she invariably gives me some sage advice. And the very biggest

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:35.200
piece she gives me is to be lazy. This is actually how she sleeps. It's kind of ridiculous.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.200
So what I mean by being lazy is, you want to make it as easy as possible for future

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:45.080
you to do as little work as possible to understand what you're writing today. So this describes

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:49.240
a lot of different things. You're basically trying to be consistent with your own work.

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:52.240
You're trying to have some patterns that you follow all the time, so it makes it really

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:56.020
intuitive for you to figure out what you're doing next.

00:00:56.020 --> 00:01:00.299
And this starts with the project structure. So unfortunately, this is a little smaller

00:01:00.299 --> 00:01:04.620
than I'd hoped. I'm sorry. This is an example of a very small project, but it does have

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:10.739
some problems. I don't know if you can see it, but there's a file called monolith.r.

00:01:10.739 --> 00:01:14.620
It's enormous. Imagine in four months from now, you're trying to find a function in this

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:19.099
enormous file. It would be pretty difficult. And there are data files in here that have

00:01:19.099 --> 00:01:22.940
names that are completely nonintuitive. If you come back to this later, are you going

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:28.379
to be able to tell what's going on? Probably not. You will be sad.

00:01:28.379 --> 00:01:32.220
So in the interest of future laziness, you can reorganize this just a little bit, do

00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:36.220
a couple minutes of work to save yourself possibly hours of work later. So what I've

00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:42.860
done here is split up that big R file so that you can tell where the global functions are,

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:46.500
where the helper functions are, where the main analysis is. And just by the names of

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:50.459
these files, you can kind of tell where you might go to find something if you're looking

00:01:50.459 --> 00:01:56.940
to update or add new data. I have also added a new data structure here, and I've renamed

00:01:56.940 --> 00:02:01.019
all the files so that the names themselves will give you a clue as to what's in them.

00:02:01.019 --> 00:02:04.660
You don't have to remember what this strange esoteric file name is if you name your files

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:09.380
in a way that it's easy to tell what's in there without having to explore them automatically.

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:13.419
So just this little bit of work today is going to make your life a lot easier later, which

00:02:13.419 --> 00:02:19.979
is exactly what my cat had suggested. In addition to that, to that being at the structure level

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:24.220
for your projects, you also want to do that within your individual files. You can pick

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:27.380
the structure that works for you as long as you're consistent so that you can tell later

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:31.380
kind of what you meant, and if you always structure it in the same way or you almost

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:35.300
order it in the same way, you're going to remember what all this means. My preferred

00:02:35.300 --> 00:02:40.020
way is to have library statements at the top, then source statements, object definitions,

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:43.259
function definitions, and then the code at the bottom. Obviously I'm going to be creating

00:02:43.259 --> 00:02:46.619
objects and functions along the way, but the global ones go at the top so I can find them

00:02:46.619 --> 00:02:53.660
easily later. And then at the statement level, you want to make these human readable as well.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:58.100
So a machine can read either of these equally well, but a human being going back and needing

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:03.139
to alter something, the second one is a whole lot easier to read. So for the rest of this

00:03:03.139 --> 00:03:06.460
presentation, my cat was so lazy that she wouldn't pose for me, so the rest of this

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:11.619
has beautiful images from the internet, so please enjoy.

00:03:11.619 --> 00:03:18.619
So, more bits of advice that she's given me. I don't know if you guys have seen this before, this is my favorite GIF ever.

00:03:18.619 --> 00:03:23.740
Try things. It's not always going to work, as you know, but try them anyway, and if they

